# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cherrypy-server
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cherrypy-server/cherrypy] CherryPy can be a web server itself or one can launch it via any WSGI compatible environment.
[src:cherrypy-server/cherrypy] It does not deal with tasks such as templating for output rendering or backend access.
[src:cherrypy-server/cherrypy] The framework is extensible with filters, which are called at defined points in the request/response processing.
[src:cherrypy-server/cherrypy] One of the goals of the project founder, Remi Delon, was to make CherryPy as pythonic as possible.
[src:cherrypy-server/cherrypy] This allows the developer to use the framework as any regular Python module and to forget (from a technical point of view) that the application is for the web.
[src:cherrypy-server/cherrypy] CherryPy doesn't force you to use a specific object-relational mapper (ORM), template language or JavaScript library.
[src:cherrypy-server/cherrypy] CherryPy wiki helps choosing a templating language.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Notable languages with OOP support include Ada, ActionScript, C++, Common Lisp, C#, Dart, Eiffel, Fortran 2003, Haxe, Java, JavaScript, Kotlin, Logo, MATLAB, Objective-C, Object Pascal, Perl, PHP, Python, R, Raku, Ruby, Scala, SIMSCRIPT, Simula, Smalltalk, Swift, Vala and Visual Basic (.NET).
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] The idea of "objects" in programming began with the artificial intelligence group at Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) in the late 1950s and early 1960s.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Here, "object" referred to LISP atoms with identified properties (attributes).
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Another early example was Sketchpad created by Ivan Sutherland at MIT in 1960–1961.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] In the glossary of his technical report, Sutherland defined terms like "object" and "instance" (with the class concept covered by "master" or "definition"), albeit specialized to graphical interaction.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Later, in 1968, AED-0, MIT's version of the ALGOL programming language, connected data structures ("plexes") and procedures, prefiguring what were later termed "messages", "methods", and "member functions".
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Topics such as data abstraction and modular programming were common points of discussion at this time.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Meanwhile, in Norway, Simula was developed during the years 1961–1967.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Simula introduced essential object-oriented ideas, such as classes, inheritance, and dynamic binding.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Simula was used mainly by researchers involved with physical modelling, like the movement of ships and their content through cargo ports.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Simula is generally accepted as being the first language with the primary features and framework of an object-oriented language.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Influenced by both MIT and Simula, Alan Kay began developing his own ideas in November 1966.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] He would go on to create Smalltalk, an influential OOP language.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] By 1967, Kay was already using the term "object-oriented programming" in conversation.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Although sometimes called the "father" of OOP, Kay has said his ideas differ from how OOP is commonly understood, and has implied that the computer science establishment did not adopt his notion.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] A 1976 MIT memo co-authored by Barbara Liskov lists Simula 67, CLU, and Alphard as object-oriented languages, but does not mention Smalltalk.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] In the 1970s, the first version of the Smalltalk programming language was developed at Xerox PARC by Alan Kay, Dan Ingalls and Adele Goldberg.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Smalltalk-72 was notable for use of objects at the language level and its graphical development environment.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Smalltalk was a fully dynamic system, allowing users to create and modify classes as they worked.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Much of the theory of OOP was developed in the context of Smalltalk, for example multiple inheritance.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] In the late 1970s and 1980s, OOP rose to prominence.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] The Flavors object-oriented Lisp was developed starting 1979, introducing multiple inheritance and mixins.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] In August 1981, Byte Magazine highlighted Smalltalk and OOP, introducing these ideas to a wide audience.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] LOOPS, the object system for Interlisp-D, was influenced by Smalltalk and Flavors, and a paper about it was published in 1982.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] In 1986, the first *Conference on Object-Oriented Programming, Systems, Languages, and Applications* (OOPSLA) was attended by 1,000 people.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] This conference marked the start of efforts to consolidate Lisp object systems, eventually resulting in the Common Lisp Object System.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] In the 1980s, there were a few attempts to design processor architectures that included hardware support for objects in memory, but these were not successful.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Examples include the Intel iAPX 432 and the Linn Smart Rekursiv.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] In the mid-1980s, new object-oriented languages like Objective-C, C++, and the Eiffel language emerged.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Objective-C was developed by Brad Cox, who had used Smalltalk at ITT Inc.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Bjarne Stroustrup created C++ based on his experience using Simula for his PhD thesis.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Bertrand Meyer produced the first design of the Eiffel language in 1985, which focused on software quality using a design by contract approach.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] In the 1990s, OOP became the main way of programming, especially as more languages supported it.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] These included Visual FoxPro 3.0, C++, and Delphi.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] OOP became even more popular with the rise of graphical user interfaces, which used objects for buttons, menus and other elements.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] One well-known example is Apple's Cocoa framework, used on macOS and written in Objective-C.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] OOP toolkits also enhanced the popularity of event-driven programming.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] At ETH Zürich, Niklaus Wirth and his colleagues created new approaches to OOP.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Modula-2 (1978) and Oberon (1987), included a distinctive approach to object orientation, classes, and type checking across module boundaries.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Inheritance is not obvious in Wirth's design since his nomenclature looks in the opposite direction: It is called type extension and the viewpoint is from the parent down to the inheritor.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Many programming languages that were initially developed before OOP was popular have been augmented with object-oriented features, including Ada, BASIC, Fortran, Pascal, and COBOL.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] The OOP features provided by languages vary.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Below are some common features of OOP languages.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Comparing OOP with other styles, like relational programming, is difficult because there isn't a clear, agreed-upon definition of OOP.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Some programming languages, like Java, provide information hiding via visibility key words (`private` and `public`).
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Some languages like Python don't provide a visibility feature, but developers might follow a convention such as starting a private member name with an underscore.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Intermediate levels of access also exist, such as Java's `protected` keyword, (which allows access from the same class and its subclasses, but not objects of a different class), and the `internal` keyword in C#, Swift, and Kotlin, which restricts access to files within the same module.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Supporters of information hiding and data abstraction say it makes code easier to reuse and intuitively represents real-world situations.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] However, others argue that OOP does not enhance readability or modularity.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Raymond has written that OOP languages tend to encourage thickly layered programs that destroy transparency.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Raymond compares this unfavourably to the approach taken with Unix and the C language.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] SOLID includes the open/closed principle, which says that classes and functions should be "open for extension, but closed for modification".
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Luca Cardelli has stated that OOP languages have "extremely poor modularity properties with respect to class extension and modification", and tend to be extremely complex.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Leo Brodie says that information hiding can lead to duplicate code, which goes against the don't repeat yourself rule of software development.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Inheritance can be supported via the class or the prototype, which have differences but use similar terms like object and instance.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] In class-based programming, the most common type of OOP, an object is an instance of a class.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] The class defines the data (variables) and methods (logic).
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] An object is created via the constructor.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Every instance of the class has the same set of variables and methods.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Classes may inherit from other classes, creating a hierarchy of classes: a case of a subclass inheriting from a super-class.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] For example, an `Employee` class might inherit from a `Person` class which endows the Employee object with the variables from `Person`.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] The subclass may add variables and methods that do not affect the super-class.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Most languages also allow the subclass to override super-class methods.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Some languages support multiple inheritance, where a class can inherit from more than one class, and other languages similarly support mixins or traits.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] For example, a mixin called UnicodeConversionMixin might add a method unicode_to_ascii() to both a FileReader and a WebPageScraper class.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] An abstract class cannot be directly instantiated as an object.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Other classes are utility classes which contain only class variables and methods and are not meant to be instantiated or subclassed.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Instead of providing a class concept, in prototype-based programming, an object is linked to another object, called its *prototype* or *parent*.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] In Self, an object may have multiple or no parents, but in the most popular prototype-based language, JavaScript, an object has exactly one prototype link, up to the base object whose prototype is null.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] A prototype acts as a model for new objects.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] For example, if you have an object `fruit`, you can make two objects `apple` and `orange` that share traits of the `fruit` prototype.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Prototype-based languages also allow objects to have their own unique properties, so the `apple` object might have an attribute `sugar_content`, while the `orange` or `fruit` objects do not.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] In all OOP languages, via object composition, an object can contain other objects.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] For example, an `Employee` object might contain an `Address` object, along with other information like `name` and `position`.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Composition is a "has-a" relationships, like "an employee has an address".
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Some languages, like Go, don't support inheritance.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Instead, they encourage "composition over inheritance", where objects are built using smaller parts instead of parent-child relationships.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] For example, instead of inheriting from class Person, the Employee class could simply contain a Person object.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] This lets the Employee class control how much of Person it exposes to other parts of the program.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Delegation is another language feature that can be used as an alternative to inheritance.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Programmers have different opinions on inheritance.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Bjarne Stroustrup, author of C++, has stated that it is possible to do OOP without inheritance.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Rob Pike has criticized inheritance for creating complex hierarchies instead of simpler solutions.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] People often think that if one class inherits from another, it means the subclass "is a" more specific version of the original class.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] This presumes the program semantics are that objects from the subclass can always replace objects from the original class without problems.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] This concept is known as behavioral subtyping, more specifically the Liskov substitution principle.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] However, this is often not true, especially in programming languages that allow mutable objects, objects that change after they are created.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] In fact, subtype polymorphism as enforced by the type checker in OOP languages cannot guarantee behavioral subtyping in most if not all contexts.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] For example, the circle-ellipse problem is notoriously difficult to handle using OOP's concept of inheritance.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Behavioral subtyping is undecidable in general, so it cannot be easily implemented by a compiler.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Because of this, programmers must carefully design class hierarchies to avoid mistakes that the programming language itself cannot catch.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] A method may be invoked via dynamic dispatch such that the method is selected at runtime instead of compile time.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] If the method choice depends on more than one type of object (such as other objects passed as parameters), it's called multiple dispatch.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] In this context, a method call is also known as message passing, meaning the method name and its inputs are like a message sent to the object for it to act on.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Dynamic dispatch works together with inheritance: if an object doesn't have the requested method, it looks up to its parent class (delegation), and continues up the chain to find a matching method.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Polymorphism in OOP refers to subtyping or subtype polymorphism, where a function can work with a specific interface and thus manipulate entities of different classes in a uniform manner.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] For example, imagine a program has two shapes: a circle and a square.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Both come from a common class called "Shape." Each shape has its own way of drawing itself.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] With subtype polymorphism, the program doesn't need to know the type of each shape, and can simply call the "Draw" method for each shape.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] The programming language runtime will ensure the correct version of the "Draw" method runs for each shape.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Because the details of each shape are handled inside their own classes, this makes the code simpler and more organized, enabling strong separation of concerns.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] An object's methods can access the object's data.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Many programming languages use a special word, like `this` or `self`, to refer to the current object.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] In languages that support open recursion, a method in an object can call other methods in the same object, including itself, using this special word.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] This allows a method in one class to call another method defined later in a subclass, a feature known as late binding.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Design patterns are common solutions to problems in software design.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Some design patterns are especially useful for OOP, and design patterns are typically introduced in an OOP context.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Sometimes, objects represent real-world things and processes in digital form.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] For example, a graphics program may have objects such as `circle`, `square`, and `menu`.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] An online shopping system might have objects such as `shopping cart`, `customer`, and `product`.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Niklaus Wirth said, "This paradigm [OOP] closely reflects the structure of systems in the real world and is therefore well suited to model complex systems with complex behavior".
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] However, more often, objects represent abstract entities, like an open file or a unit converter.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Not everyone agrees that OOP makes it easy to copy the real world exactly or that doing so is even necessary.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Bob Martin suggests that because classes are software, their relationships don't match the real-world relationships they represent.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Bertrand Meyer argues that a program is not a model of the world but a model of some part of the world; "Reality is a cousin twice removed".
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Steve Yegge noted that natural languages lack the OOP approach of naming a thing (object) before an action (method), as opposed to functional programming which does the reverse.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] This can make an OOP solution more complex than one written via procedural programming.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] The following are notable software design patterns for OOP objects.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] A common anti-pattern is the God object, an object that knows or does too much.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Both OOP and relational database management systems (RDBMSs) are widely used in software today.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] However, relational databases don't store objects directly, which creates a challenge when using them together.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] This issue is called object-relational impedance mismatch.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] To solve this problem, developers use different methods, but none of them are perfect.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] One of the most common solutions is object-relational mapping (ORM), which helps connect object-oriented programs to relational databases.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Examples of ORM tools include Visual FoxPro, Java Data Objects, and Ruby on Rails ActiveRecord.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Some databases, called object databases, are designed to work with OOP.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] However, they have not been as popular or successful as relational databases.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Date and Darwen have proposed a theoretical foundation that uses OOP as a kind of customizable type system to support RDBMSs, but it forbids objects containing pointers to other objects.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] In responsibility-driven design, classes are built around what they need to do and the information they share, in the form of a contract.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] This is different from data-driven design, where classes are built based on the data they need to store.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] According to Wirfs-Brock and Wilkerson, the originators of responsibility-driven design, responsibility-driven design is the better approach.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Researchers have tried to formally define the semantics of OOP.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Inheritance presents difficulties, particularly with the interactions between open recursion and encapsulated state.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Researchers have used recursive types and co-algebraic data types to incorporate essential features of OOP.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Abadi and Cardelli defined several extensions of System F<: that deal with mutable objects, allowing both subtype polymorphism and parametric polymorphism (generics), and were able to formally model many OOP concepts and constructs.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Although far from trivial, static analysis of object-oriented programming languages such as Java is a mature field, with several commercial tools.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Many popular programming languages, like C++, Java, and Python, use OOP.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] In the past, OOP was widely accepted, but recently, some programmers have criticized it and prefer functional programming instead.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] A study by Potok et al. found no major difference in productivity between OOP and procedural programming.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Some believe that OOP places too much focus on using objects rather than on algorithms and data structures.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] For example, programmer Rob Pike pointed out that OOP can make programmers think more about type hierarchy than composition.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] He has called OOP "the Roman numerals of computing".
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Rich Hickey, creator of Clojure, described OOP as overly simplistic, especially when it comes to representing real-world things that change over time.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Alexander Stepanov said that OOP tries to fit everything into a single type, which can be limiting.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] He argued that sometimes we need multisorted algebras: families of interfaces that span multiple types, such as in generic programming.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Stepanov also said that calling everything an "object" doesn't add much understanding.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] OOP was created to make code easier to reuse and maintain.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] However, it was not designed to clearly show the flow of a program's instructions.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] As computers began using more parallel processing and multiple threads, it became more important to understand and control how instructions flow.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Paul Graham believes big companies like OOP because it helps manage large teams of average programmers.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] He argues that OOP adds structure, making it harder for one person to make serious mistakes, but at the same time restrains smart programmers.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Raymond, a Unix programmer and open-source software advocate, argues that OOP is not the best way to write programs.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Richard Feldman says that, while OOP features helped some languages stay organized, their popularity comes from other reasons.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Lawrence Krubner argues that OOP doesn't offer special advantages compared to other styles, like functional programming, and can complicate coding.
[src:cherrypy-server/object-oriented-programming] Luca Cardelli says that OOP is slower and takes longer to compile than procedural programming.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Guido van Rossum began working on Python in the late 1980s as a successor to the ABC programming language.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Python 3.0, released in 2008, was a major revision and not completely backward-compatible with earlier versions.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Beginning with Python 3.5, capabilities and keywords for typing were added to the language, allowing optional static typing.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] As of 2026, the Python Software Foundation supports Python 3.10, 3.11, 3.12, 3.13, and 3.14, following the project's annual release cycle and five-year support policy.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Python 3.15 is currently in the beta development phase, and the stable release is expected to launch in October 2026.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Earlier versions in the 3.x series have reached end-of-life and no longer receive security updates.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Python has gained extensive use in the machine learning community.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] It is widely taught as an introductory programming language.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Since 2003, Python has consistently ranked among the top ten most popular programming languages in the TIOBE Programming Community Index, which ranks programming languages based on searches across 24 platforms.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Python was conceived in the late 1980s by Guido van Rossum at Centrum Wiskunde & Informatica (CWI) in the Netherlands.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] It was designed as a successor to the ABC programming language, which was inspired by SETL, capable of exception handling and interfacing with the Amoeba operating system.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Python implementation began in December 1989.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Van Rossum first released it in 1991 as Python 0.9.0.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] In January 2019, active Python core developers elected a five-member Steering Council to lead the project.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] The name *Python* derives from the British comedy series *Monty Python's Flying Circus*.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Python 2.0 was released on 16 October 2000, featuring many new features such as list comprehensions, cycle-detecting garbage collection, reference counting, and Unicode support.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Python 2.7's end-of-life was initially set for 2015, and then postponed to 2020 out of concern that a large body of existing code could not easily be forward-ported to Python 3.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] It no longer receives security patches or updates.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] While Python 2.7 and older versions are officially unsupported, a different unofficial Python implementation, PyPy, continues to support Python 2, i.e., "2.7.18+" (plus 3.11), with the plus signifying (at least some) "backported security updates".
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Python 3.0 was released on 3 December 2008, and was a major revision and not completely backward-compatible with earlier versions, with some new semantics and changed syntax.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Python 2.7.18, released in 2020, was the last release of Python 2.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Several releases in the Python 3.x series have added new syntax to the language, and made a few (considered very minor) backward-incompatible changes.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] As of May 2026, Python 3.14.6 is the latest stable release.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] All older 3.x versions had a security update down to Python 3.9.24 then again with 3.9.25, the final version in 3.9 series.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Python 3.10 is, since November 2025, the oldest supported branch.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Python 3.15 has an alpha released, and Android has an official downloadable executable available for Python 3.14.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Releases receive two years of full support followed by three years of security support.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Python is a multi-paradigm programming language.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Object-oriented programming and structured programming are fully supported, and many of their features support functional programming and aspect-oriented programming – including metaprogramming and metaobjects.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Many other paradigms are supported via extensions, including design by contract and logic programming.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Python is often referred to as a *'glue language'* because it is purposely designed to be able to integrate components written in other languages.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Python uses dynamic typing and a combination of reference counting and a cycle-detecting garbage collector for memory management.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] It uses dynamic name resolution (late binding), which binds method and variable names during program execution.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Python's design offers some support for functional programming in the "Lisp tradition".
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] It has `filter`, `map`, and `reduce` functions; list comprehensions, dictionaries, sets, and generator expressions.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] The standard library has two modules (`itertools` and `functools`) that implement functional tools borrowed from Haskell and Standard ML.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] However, Python has received criticism for violating these principles and adding unnecessary language bloat.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Responses to these criticisms note that the Zen of Python is a guideline rather than a rule.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] The addition of some new features had been controversial: Guido van Rossum resigned as *Benevolent Dictator for Life* after conflict about adding the assignment expression operator in Python 3.8.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Nevertheless, rather than building all functionality into its core, Python was designed to be highly extensible through modules.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] This compact modularity has made it particularly popular as a means of adding programmable interfaces to existing applications.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Van Rossum's vision of a small core language with a large standard library and an easily extensible interpreter stemmed from his frustrations with ABC, which represented the opposite approach.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Python claims to strive for a simpler, less-cluttered syntax and grammar, while giving developers a choice in their coding methodology.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Python lacks `do .. while` loops, which Rossum considered harmful.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] In contrast to Perl's motto "there is more than one way to do it", Python advocates an approach where "there should be one – and preferably only one – obvious way to do it".
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] In practice, however, Python provides many ways to achieve a given goal.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] There are at least three ways to format a string literal, with no certainty as to which one a programmer should use.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Python's developers typically prioritize readability over performance.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] For example, they reject patches to non-critical parts of the CPython reference implementation that would offer increases in speed that do not justify the cost of clarity and readability.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Execution speed can be improved by moving speed-critical functions to extension modules written in languages such as C, or by using a just-in-time compiler like PyPy.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Also, it is possible to transpile to other languages.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] However, this approach either fails to achieve the expected speed-up, since Python is a very dynamic language, or only a restricted subset of Python is compiled (with potential minor semantic changes).
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Python is meant to be a fun language to use.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] This goal is reflected in the name – a tribute to the British comedy group Monty Python – and in playful approaches to some tutorials and reference materials.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] For instance, some code examples use the terms "spam" and "eggs" (in reference to a Monty Python sketch), rather than the typical terms "foo" and "bar".
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] A common neologism in the Python community is *pythonic*, which has a broad range of meanings related to program style: Pythonic code may use Python idioms well; be natural or show fluency in the language; or conform with Python's minimalist philosophy and emphasis on readability.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] There are 3 kinds of PEPs, with those are being *standards track PEP*, *Informational PEP* and *Process PEP*s which has their own unique meanings.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] They were firstly introduced in 2000, inspired by other RfCs (requests for comments) and Desing Enhancement Proposals.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Most known PEPs are PEP – 1, PEP – 8, PEP – 20, PEP – 257 and others.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Python is meant to be an easily readable language.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Its formatting is visually uncluttered and often uses English keywords where other languages use punctuation.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Unlike many other languages, it does not use curly brackets to delimit blocks, and semicolons after statements are allowed but rarely used.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] It has fewer syntactic exceptions and special cases than C or Pascal.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Python uses whitespace indentation, rather than curly brackets or keywords, to delimit blocks.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] An increase in indentation comes after certain statements; a decrease in indentation signifies the end of the current block.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Thus, the program's visual structure accurately represents its semantic structure.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] This feature is sometimes termed the off-side rule.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Some other languages use indentation this way; but in most, indentation has no semantic meaning.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] The recommended indent size is four spaces.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] The assignment statement (`=`) binds a name as a reference to a separate, dynamically allocated object.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Variables may subsequently be rebound at any time to any object.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] In Python, a variable name is a generic reference holder without a fixed data type; however, it always refers to *some* object with a type.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] This is called dynamic typing—in contrast to statically-typed languages, where each variable may contain only a value of a certain type.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Python does not support tail call optimization or first-class continuations; according to Van Rossum, the language never will.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] However, better support for coroutine-like functionality is provided by extending Python's generators.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Before 2.5, generators were lazy iterators; data was passed unidirectionally out of the generator.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] From Python 2.5 on, it is possible to pass data back into a generator function; and from version 3.3, data can be passed through multiple stack levels.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] In Python, a distinction between expressions and statements is rigidly enforced, in contrast to languages such as Common Lisp, Scheme, or Ruby.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] A statement cannot be part of an expression; because of this restriction, expressions such as list and `dict` comprehensions (and lambda expressions) cannot contain statements.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] As a particular case, an assignment statement such as `a = 1` cannot be part of the conditional expression of a conditional statement.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Python uses duck typing, and it has typed objects but untyped variable names.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Type constraints are not checked at definition time; rather, operations on an object may fail at usage time, indicating that the object is not of an appropriate type.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Despite being dynamically typed, Python is strongly typed, forbidding operations that are poorly defined (e.g., adding a number and a string) rather than quietly attempting to interpret them.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Python allows programmers to define their own types using classes, most often for object-oriented programming.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] New instances of classes are constructed by calling the class, for example, `SpamClass()` or `EggsClass()`); the classes are instances of the metaclass `type` (which is an instance of itself), thereby allowing metaprogramming and reflection.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Before version 3.0, Python had two kinds of classes, both using the same syntax: *old-style* and *new-style*.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Current Python versions support the semantics of only the new style.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Python supports optional type annotations.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] These annotations are not enforced by the language, but may be used by external tools such as **mypy** to catch errors.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Python includes a module `typing` including several type names for type annotations.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Also, mypy supports a Python compiler called mypyc, which leverages type annotations for optimization.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Python includes conventional symbols for arithmetic operators (`+`, `-`, `*`, `/`), the floor-division operator `//`, and the modulo operator `%`.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] (With the modulo operator, a remainder can be negative, e.g., `4 % -3 == -2`.) Python also offers the `**` symbol for exponentiation, e.g.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] These operators work as in traditional mathematics; with the same precedence rules, the infix operators `+` and `-` can also be unary, to represent positive and negative numbers respectively.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Division between integers produces floating-point results.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] In Python terms, the `/` operator represents *true division* (or simply *division*), while the `//` operator represents *floor division.* Before version 3.0, the `/` operator represents *classic division*.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Rounding towards negative infinity, though a different method than in most languages, adds consistency to Python.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] For instance, this rounding implies that the equation `(a + b)//b == a//b + 1` is always true.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Also, the rounding implies that the equation `b*(a//b) + a%b == a` is valid for both positive and negative values of `a`.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] As expected, the result of `a%b` lies in the half-open interval [0, *b*), where `b` is a positive integer; however, maintaining the validity of the equation requires that the result must lie in the interval (*b*, 0] when `b` is negative.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Python provides a `round` function for rounding a float to the nearest integer.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] For tie-breaking, Python 3 uses the *round to even* method: `round(1.5)` and `round(2.5)` both produce `2`.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Python allows Boolean expressions that contain multiple equality relations to be consistent with general usage in mathematics.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] For example, the expression `a < b < c` tests whether `a` is less than `b` and `b` is less than `c`.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] C-derived languages interpret this expression differently: in C, the expression would first evaluate `a < b`, resulting in 0 or 1, and that result would then be compared with `c`.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Python uses arbitrary-precision arithmetic for all integer operations.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] The `Decimal` type/class in the `decimal` module provides decimal floating-point numbers to a pre-defined arbitrary precision with several rounding modes.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] The `Fraction` class in the `fractions` module provides arbitrary precision for rational numbers.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Due to Python's extensive mathematics library and the third-party library NumPy, the language is frequently used for scientific scripting in tasks such as numerical data processing and manipulation.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Functions are created in Python by using the `def` keyword.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] A function is defined similarly to how it is called, by first providing the function name and then the required parameters.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] To assign a default value to a function parameter in case no actual value is provided at run time, variable-definition syntax can be used inside the function header.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Python's large standard library is commonly cited as one of its greatest strengths.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] For Internet-facing applications, many standard formats and protocols such as MIME and HTTP are supported.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] The language includes modules for creating graphical user interfaces, connecting to relational databases, generating pseudorandom numbers, arithmetic with arbitrary-precision decimals, manipulating regular expressions, and unit testing.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Some parts of the standard library are covered by specifications—for example, the Web Server Gateway Interface (WSGI) implementation `wsgiref` follows PEP 333—but most parts are specified by their code, internal documentation, and test suites.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] However, because most of the standard library is cross-platform Python code, only a few modules must be altered or rewritten for variant implementations.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] As of 13 March 2025, the Python Package Index (PyPI), the official repository for third-party Python software, contains over 614,339 packages.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Most Python implementations (including CPython) include a read–eval–print loop (REPL); this permits the environment to function as a command line interpreter, with which users enter statements sequentially and receive results immediately.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Also, CPython is bundled with an integrated development environment (IDE) called IDLE, which is oriented toward beginners.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Other shells, including IDLE and IPython, add additional capabilities such as improved auto-completion, session-state retention, and syntax highlighting.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] CPython is the reference implementation of Python.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] This implementation is written in C, meeting the C11 standard since version 3.11.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Older versions use the C89 standard with several select C99 features, but third-party extensions are not limited to older C versions—e.g., they can be implemented using C11 or C++.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] CPython compiles Python programs into an intermediate bytecode, which is then executed by a virtual machine.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] CPython is distributed with a large standard library written in a combination of C and native Python.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] CPython is available for many platforms, including Windows and most modern Unix-like systems, including macOS (and Apple M1 Macs, since Python 3.9.1, using an experimental installer).
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Starting with Python 3.9, the Python installer intentionally fails to install on Windows 7 and 8; Windows XP was supported until Python 3.5.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Old Python versions unofficially support VMS (mostly supporting) and OpenVMS x86-64 has Python 3.10 support.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Platform portability was one of Python's earliest priorities.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] During development of Python 1 and 2, even OS/2 and Solaris were supported; since that time, support has been dropped for many platforms.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] All current Python versions (since 3.7) support only operating systems that feature multithreading, by now supporting not nearly as many operating systems (dropping many outdated) than in the past.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] All alternative implementations have at least slightly different semantics.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] For example, an alternative may include unordered dictionaries, in contrast to other current Python versions.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] As another example in the larger Python ecosystem, PyPy does not support the full C Python API.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Creating an executable with Python often is done by bundling an entire Python interpreter into the executable, which causes binary sizes to be massive for small programs, yet there exist implementations that are capable of truly compiling Python.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Stackless Python is a significant fork of CPython that implements microthreads.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] This implementation uses the call stack differently, thus allowing massively concurrent programs.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] A performance comparison among various Python implementations, using a non-numerical (combinatorial) workload, was presented at EuroSciPy '13.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] In addition, Python's performance relative to other programming languages is benchmarked by The Computer Language Benchmarks Game.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] There are several approaches to optimizing Python performance, despite the inherent slowness of an interpreted language.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Python's development is conducted mostly through the *Python Enhancement Proposal* (PEP) process; this process is the primary mechanism for proposing major new features, collecting community input on issues, and documenting Python design decisions.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Python coding style is covered in PEP 8.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Outstanding PEPs are reviewed and commented on by the Python community and the steering council.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Enhancement of the language corresponds with development of the CPython reference implementation.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] The mailing list python-dev is the primary forum for the language's development.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Specific issues were originally discussed in the Roundup bug tracker hosted by the foundation.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] In 2022, all issues and discussions were migrated to GitHub.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Development originally took place on a self-hosted source-code repository running Mercurial, until Python moved to GitHub in January 2017.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Many alpha, beta, and release-candidates are also released as previews and for testing before final releases.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Although there is a rough schedule for releases, they are often delayed if the code is not ready yet.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Python's development team monitors the state of the code by running a large unit test suite during development.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] The major academic conference on Python is PyCon.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Also, there are special Python mentoring programs, such as PyLadies.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Python's name is inspired by the British comedy group Monty Python, whom Python creator Guido van Rossum enjoyed while developing the language.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Monty Python references appear frequently in Python code and culture; for example, the metasyntactic variables often used in Python literature are *spam* and *eggs*, rather than the traditional *foo* and *bar*.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Also, the official Python documentation contains various references to Monty Python routines.
[src:cherrypy-server/python-programming-language] Python users are sometimes referred to as "Pythonistas".
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] This tutorial will walk you through basic but complete CherryPy applications that will show you common concepts as well as slightly more advanced ones.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] The following example demonstrates the most basic application you could write with CherryPy.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] The first three lines indicate the server will handle `signal` for you.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] The next line tells you the current state of the server, as that point it is in `STARTING` stage.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Then, you are notified your application has no specific configuration set to it.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Next, the server starts a couple of internal utilities that we will explain later.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Finally, the server indicates it is now ready to accept incoming communications as it listens on the address `127.0.0.1:8080`.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] In other words, at that stage your application is ready to be used.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Before moving on, let’s discuss the message regarding the lack of configuration.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] By default, CherryPy has a feature which will review the syntax correctness of settings you could provide to configure the application.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] When none are provided, a warning message is thus displayed in the logs.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] That log is harmless and will not prevent CherryPy from working.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] You can refer to the documentation above to understand how to set the configuration.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Your applications will obviously handle more than a single URL.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Go now to http://localhost:8080/generate and your browser will display a random string.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Let’s take a minute to decompose what’s happening here.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] In the previous tutorial, we have seen how to create an application that could generate a random string.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Let’s now assume you wish to indicate the length of that string dynamically.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Go now to http://localhost:8080/generate?length=16 and your browser will display a generated string of length 16.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Notice how we benefit from Python’s default arguments’ values to support URLs such as http://localhost:8080/generate still.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] In a URL such as this one, the section after `?` is called a query-string.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Traditionally, the query-string is used to contextualize the URL by passing a set of (key, value) pairs.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] The format for those pairs is `key=value`.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Each pair being separated by a `&` character.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Notice how we have to convert the given `length` value to an integer.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Indeed, values are sent out from the client to our server as strings.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Much like CherryPy maps URL path segments to exposed functions, query-string keys are mapped to those exposed function parameters.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] CherryPy is a web framework upon which you build web applications.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] The most traditional shape taken by applications is through an HTML user-interface speaking to your CherryPy server.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Let’s see how to handle HTML forms via the following example.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Go now to http://localhost:8080/ and your browser and this will display a simple input field to indicate the length of the string you want to generate.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Notice that in this example, the form uses the `GET` method and when you pressed the `Give it now!` button, the form is sent using the same URL as in the previous tutorial.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] HTML forms also support the `POST` method, in that case the query-string is not appended to the URL but it sent as the body of the client’s request to the server.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] However, this would not change your application’s exposed method because CherryPy handles both the same way and uses the exposed’s handler parameters to deal with the query-string (key, value) pairs.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] It’s not uncommon that an application needs to follow the user’s activity for a while.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] The usual mechanism is to use a session identifier that is carried during the conversation between the user and your application.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] In this example, we generate the string as in the previous tutorial but also store it in the current session.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] If you go to http://localhost:8080/, generate a random string, then go to http://localhost:8080/display, you will see the string you just generated.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] The lines 30-34 show you how to enable the session support in your CherryPy application.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] By default, CherryPy will save sessions in the process’s memory.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] It supports more persistent backends as well.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Web applications are usually also made of static content such as javascript, CSS files or images.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] CherryPy provides support to serve static content to end-users.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Let’s assume, you want to associate a stylesheet with your application to display a blue background color (why not?).
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] First, save the following stylesheet into a file named `style.css` and stored into a local directory `public/css`.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Now let’s update the HTML code so that we link to the stylesheet using the http://localhost:8080/static/css/style.css URL.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Going to http://localhost:8080/, you should be greeted by a flashy blue color.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] CherryPy provides support to serve a single file or a complete directory structure.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Most of the time, this is what you’ll end up doing so this is what the code above demonstrates.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] First, we indicate the `root` directory of all of our static content.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] This must be an absolute path for security reason.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] CherryPy will complain if you provide only relative paths when looking for a match to your URLs.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Then we indicate that all URLs which path segment starts with `/static` will be served as static content.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] We map that URL to the `public` directory, a direct child of the `root` directory.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] The entire sub-tree of the `public` directory will be served as static content.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] CherryPy will map URLs to path within that directory.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] This is why `/static/css/style.css` is found in `public/css/style.css`.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] It’s not unusual nowadays that web applications expose some sort of datamodel or computation functions.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Without going into its details, one strategy is to follow the REST principles edicted by Roy T.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Roughly speaking, it assumes that you can identify a resource and that you can address that resource through that identifier.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Well, mostly, these principles are there to ensure that you decouple, as best as you can, the entities your application expose from the way they are manipulated or consumed.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] To embrace this point of view, developers will usually design a web API that expose pairs of `(URL, HTTP method, data, constraints)`.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] You will often hear REST and web API together.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] The former is one strategy to provide the latter.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] This tutorial will not go deeper in that whole web API concept as it’s a much more engaging subject, but you ought to read more about it online.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Lets go through a small example of a very basic web API mildly following REST principles.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Before we see it in action, let’s explain a few things.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Until now, CherryPy was creating a tree of exposed methods that were used to match URLs.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] In the case of our web API, we want to stress the role played by the actual requests’ HTTP methods.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] So we created methods that are named after them and they are all exposed at once by decorating the class itself with `cherrypy.expose`.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] However, we must then switch from the default mechanism of matching URLs to method for one that is aware of the whole HTTP method shenanigan.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] This is what goes on line 27 where we create a `MethodDispatcher` instance.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Then we force the responses `content-type` to be `text/plain` and we finally ensure that `GET` requests will only be responded to clients that accept that `content-type` by having a `Accept: text/plain` header set in their request.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] However, we do this only for that HTTP method as it wouldn’t have much meaning on the other methods.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] For the purpose of this tutorial, we will be using a Python client rather than your browser as we wouldn’t be able to actually try our web API otherwise.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] The first and last `500` responses stem from the fact that, in the first case, we haven’t yet generated a string through `POST` and, on the latter case, that it doesn’t exist after we’ve deleted it.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Lines 12-14 show you how the application reacted when our client requested the generated string as a JSON format.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Since we configured the web API to only support plain text, it returns the appropriate HTTP error code.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] We use the Session interface of `requests` so that it takes care of carrying the session id stored in the request cookie in each subsequent request.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] It’s all about RESTful URLs these days, isn’t it?
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] It is likely your URL will be made of dynamic parts that you will not be able to match to page handlers.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] For example, `/library/12/book/15` cannot be directly handled by the default CherryPy dispatcher since the segments `12` and `15` will not be matched to any Python callable.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] This can be easily workaround with two handy CherryPy features explained in the advanced section.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] In the recent years, web applications have moved away from the simple pattern of “HTML forms + refresh the whole page”.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] This traditional scheme still works very well but users have become used to web applications that don’t refresh the entire page.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Broadly speaking, web applications carry code performed client-side that can speak with the backend without having to refresh the whole page.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] This tutorial will involve a little more code this time around.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] First, let’s see our CSS stylesheet located in `public/css/style.css`.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] We’re adding a simple rule about the element that will display the generated string.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Save the following HTML code into a file named `index.html`.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] We’ll be using the jQuery framework out of simplicity but feel free to replace it with your favourite tool.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] The page is composed of simple HTML elements to get user input and display the generated string.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] It also contains client-side code to talk to the backend API that actually performs the hard work.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Finally, here’s the application’s code that serves the HTML page above and responds to requests to generate strings.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Both are hosted by the same application server.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Go to http://127.0.0.1:8080/ and play with the input and buttons to generate, replace or delete the strings.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Notice how the page isn’t refreshed, simply part of its content.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Notice as well how your frontend converses with the backend using a straightfoward, yet clean, web service API.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] That same API could easily be used by non-HTML clients.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Until now, all the generated strings were saved in the session, which by default is stored in the process memory.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Though, you can persist sessions on disk or in a distributed memory store, this is not the right way of keeping your data on the long run.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Sessions are there to identify your user and carry as little amount of data as necessary for the operation carried by the user.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] To store, persist and query data you need a proper database server.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Let’s focus on the relational ones since they are the most common and probably what you will want to learn first.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] For the sake of reducing the number of dependencies for these tutorials, we will go for the `sqlite` database which is directly supported by Python.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Our application will replace the storage of the generated string from the session to a SQLite database.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] The application will have the same HTML code as tutorial 08.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Let’s first see how we create two functions that create and destroy the table within our database.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] These functions are registered to the CherryPy’s server on lines 85-86, so that they are called when the server starts and stops.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Next, notice how we replaced all the session code with calls to the database.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] We use the session id to identify the user’s string within our database.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Since the session will go away after a while, it’s probably not the right approach.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] A better idea would be to associate the user’s login or more resilient unique identifier.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] For the sake of our demo, this should do.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] In this example, we must still set the session to a dummy value so that the session is not discarded on each request by CherryPy.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Since we now use the database to store the generated string, we simply store a dummy timestamp inside the session.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Unfortunately, sqlite in Python forbids us to share a connection between threads.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Since CherryPy is a multi-threaded server, this would be an issue.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] This is the reason why we open and close a connection to the database on each call.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] This is clearly not really production friendly, and it is probably advisable to either use a more capable database engine or a higher level library, such as SQLAlchemy, to better support your application’s needs.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] In the recent years, client-side single-page applications (SPA) have gradually eaten server-side generated content web applications’s lunch.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] This tutorial demonstrates how to integrate with React.js, a Javascript library for SPA released by Facebook in 2013.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Please refer to React.js documentation to learn more about it.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] To demonstrate it, let’s use the code from tutorial 09.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] However, we will be replacing the HTML and Javascript code.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Basically, we have removed the entire Javascript code that was using jQuery.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] What a lot of code for something so simple, isn’t it?
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] The entry point is the last few lines where we indicate that we want to render the HTML code of the `StringGeneratorBox` React.js class inside the `generator` div.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] When the page is rendered, so is that component.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Notice how it is also made of another component that renders the form itself.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] This might be a little over the top for such a simple example but hopefully will get you started with React.js in the process.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] There is not much to say and, hopefully, the meaning of that code is rather clear.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] The component has an internal state in which we store the current string as generated/modified by the user.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] When the user changes the content of the input boxes, the state is updated on the client side.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Then, when a button is clicked, that state is sent out to the backend server using the API endpoint and the appropriate action takes places.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Then, the state is updated and so is the view.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] CherryPy comes with a powerful architecture that helps you organizing your code in a way that should make it easier to maintain and more flexible.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] In spite of being really simplistic, this is not far from how your application behaves.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] CherryPy helps you structure your application in a way that mirrors these high-level ideas.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] To support these use-cases, CherryPy provides a mechanism called a dispatcher.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] A dispatcher is executed early during the request processing in order to determine which piece of code of your application will handle the incoming request.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Or, to continue on the store analogy, a dispatcher will decide which till to lead a customer to.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Let’s assume your store has decided to operate a discount spree but, only for a specific category of customers.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] CherryPy will deal with such use case via a mechanism called a tool.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] A tool is a piece of code that runs on a per-request basis in order to perform additional work.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Usually a tool is a simple Python function that is executed at a given point during the process of the request by CherryPy.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] As we have seen, the store has a crew of people dedicated to manage the stock and deal with any customers’ expectation.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] In the CherryPy world, this translates into having functions that run outside of any request life-cycle.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] These functions should take care of background tasks, long lived connections (such as those to a database for instance), etc.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Plugins are called that way because they work along with the CherryPy engine and extend it with your operations.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] We now have a neat way that we can exercise our application making tests.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] Of course it is because that is only executed when the python program is started directly.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] When you rerun the code coverage, it should show 100% now.
[src:cherrypy-server/tutorials] When using in CI, you might want to integrate Codecov, Landscape or Coveralls into your project to store and track coverage data over time.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-gateway-interface] The **Web Server Gateway Interface** (**WSGI**, pronounced *whiskey* or *WIZ-ghee*) is a simple calling convention for web servers to forward requests to web applications or frameworks written in the Python programming language.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-gateway-interface] The current version of WSGI, version 1.0.1, is specified in Python Enhancement Proposal (PEP) 3333.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-gateway-interface] WSGI was originally specified as PEP-333 in 2003.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-gateway-interface] PEP-3333, published in 2010, updates the specification for Python 3.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-gateway-interface] In 2003, Python web frameworks were typically written against only CGI, FastCGI, mod_python, or some other custom API of a specific web server.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-gateway-interface] WSGI was thus created as an implementation-neutral interface between web servers and web applications or frameworks to promote common ground for portable web application development.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-gateway-interface] Between the server and the application, there may be one or more *WSGI middleware components*, which implement both sides of the API, typically in Python code.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-gateway-interface] WSGI does not specify how the Python interpreter should be started, nor how the application object should be loaded or configured, and different frameworks and webservers achieve this in different ways.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-gateway-interface] A WSGI middleware component is a Python callable that is itself a WSGI application, but may handle requests by delegating to other WSGI applications.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-gateway-interface] These applications can themselves be WSGI middleware components.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-gateway-interface] A full example of a WSGI network server is outside the scope of this article.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-gateway-interface] Below is a sketch of how one would call a WSGI application and retrieve its HTTP status line, response headers, and response body, as Python objects.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-gateway-interface] Details of how to construct the `environ` dict have been omitted.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-gateway-interface] Currently wrappers are available for FastCGI, CGI, SCGI, AJP (using flup), twisted.web, Apache (using mod_wsgi or mod_python), Nginx (using ngx_http_uwsgi_module), Nginx Unit (using the Python language module), and Microsoft IIS (using WFastCGI, isapi-wsgi, PyISAPIe, or an ASP gateway).
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] A **web server** is computer software that accepts requests via HTTP (the network protocol created to distribute web content) or its secure variant HTTPS.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] A user agent, commonly a web browser or web crawler, initiates communication by making a request for a web page or other resource using HTTP, and the server responds with the content of that resource or an error message.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] A web server can also accept and store resources sent from the user agent if configured to do so.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] The hardware used to run a web server can vary according to the volume of requests that it needs to handle.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] At the low end of the range are embedded systems, such as a router that runs a small web server as its configuration interface.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] A high-traffic Internet website might handle requests with hundreds of servers that run on racks of high-speed computers.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] A resource sent from a web server can be a pre-existing file (static content) available to the web server, or it can be generated at the time of the request (dynamic content) by another program that communicates with the server software.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] The former usually can be served faster and can be more easily cached for repeated requests, while the latter supports a broader range of applications.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] Technologies such as REST and SOAP, which use HTTP as a basis for general computer-to-computer communication, as well as support for WebDAV extensions, have extended the application of web servers well beyond their original purpose of serving human-readable pages.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] In March 1989, Sir Tim Berners-Lee proposed a new project to his employer CERN, with the goal of easing the exchange of information between scientists by using a hypertext system.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] The proposal titled *"HyperText and CERN"*, asked for comments and it was read by several people.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] In October 1990 the proposal was reformulated and enriched (having as co-author Robert Cailliau), and finally, it was approved.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] Those early browsers retrieved web pages written in a simple early form of HTML from web servers using a new basic communication protocol that was named HTTP 0.9.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] In August 1991 Tim Berners-Lee announced the *birth of WWW technology* and encouraged scientists to adopt and develop it.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] Soon after, those programs, along with their source code, were made available to people interested in their usage.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] Although the source code was not formally licensed or placed in the public domain, CERN informally allowed users and developers to experiment and further develop on top of them.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] Berners-Lee started promoting the adoption and the usage of those programs along with their porting to other operating systems.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] In December 1991, the **first web server outside Europe** was installed at SLAC (U.S.A.).
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] This was a very important event because it started trans-continental web communications between web browsers and web servers.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] In 1991–1993, CERN web server program continued to be actively developed by the www group, meanwhile, thanks to the availability of its source code and the public specifications of the HTTP protocol, many other implementations of web servers started to be developed.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] In April 1993, CERN issued a public official statement stating that the three components of Web software (the basic line-mode client, the web server and the library of common code), along with their source code, were put in the public domain.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] This statement freed web server developers from any possible legal issue about the development of *derivative work* based on that source code (a threat that in practice never existed).
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] At the beginning of 1994, the most notable among new web servers was NCSA httpd which ran on a variety of Unix-based OSs and could serve *dynamically generated content* by implementing the `POST` HTTP method and the CGI to communicate with external programs.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] These capabilities, along with the multimedia features of NCSA's Mosaic browser (also able to manage HTML FORMs in order to send data to a web server) highlighted the potential of web technology for publishing and distributed computing applications.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] At the beginning of 1995 those patches were all applied to the last release of NCSA source code and, after several tests, the Apache HTTP server project was started.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] At the end of 1994, a new commercial web server, named Netsite, was released with specific features.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] It was the first one of many other similar products that were developed first by Netscape, then also by Sun Microsystems, and finally by Oracle Corporation.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] In mid-1995, the first version of IIS was released by Microsoft for Windows NT OS.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] This marked the entry, in the field of World Wide Web technologies, of a commercial developer and vendor that has played and still is playing a key role on both sides (client and server) of the web.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] In the second half of 1995, CERN and NCSA web servers started to decline (in global percentage usage) because of the widespread adoption of new web servers which had a much faster development cycle along with more features, more fixes applied, and more performances than the previous ones.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] At the end of 1996, there were already over fifty known, different web-server-software programs that were available to everybody who wanted to own an Internet domain name or to host websites.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] Many of them lived only shortly and were replaced by other web servers.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] The publication of RFCs about protocol versions HTTP/1.0 (1996) and HTTP/1.1 (1997, 1999), forced most web servers to comply (not always completely) with those standards.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] The use of TCP/IP persistent connections (HTTP/1.1) required web servers both to increase the maximum number of concurrent connections allowed and to improve their level of scalability.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] Between 1996 and 1999, Netscape Enterprise Server and Microsoft's IIS emerged among the leading commercial options whereas among the freely available and open-source programs Apache HTTP Server held the lead as the preferred server (because of its reliability and its many features).
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] In those years there was also another commercial web server called Zeus (*now discontinued*) that was known as one of the fastest and most scalable web servers available on market, at least till the first decade of 2000s, despite its low percentage of usage.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] Apache resulted in the most used web server from mid-1996 to the end of 2015 when, after a few years of decline, it was surpassed initially by IIS and then by Nginx.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] Afterward IIS dropped to much lower percentages of usage than Apache (see also market share).
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] From 2005–2006, Apache started to improve its speed and its scalability level by introducing new performance features (e.g., event MPM and new content cache).
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] A few years after 2000 started, not only other commercial and highly competitive web servers (e.g., LiteSpeed) but also many other open-source programs such as Hiawatha, Cherokee HTTP server, Lighttpd, Nginx and other derived and related products also available with commercial support emerged.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] Within a year, these changes, on average, nearly tripled the maximum number of persistent connections that web servers had to manage.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] In 2015, RFCs published new protocol version [HTTP/2], and as the implementation of new specifications was not trivial at all, a **dilemma arose among developers of less popular web servers** (e.g., with a percentage of usage lower than 1% ..
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] 2%), about adding or not adding support for that new protocol version.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] In 2020–2021 the HTTP/2 dynamics about its implementation (by top web servers and popular web browsers) were partly replicated after the publication of advanced drafts of future RFC about HTTP/3 protocol.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] The following technical overview should be considered only as an attempt to give a few very *limited examples* about *some* features that may be implemented in a web server and *some* of the tasks that it may perform in order to have a sufficiently wide scenario about the topic.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] A **web server program** plays the role of a server in a client–server model by implementing one or more versions of HTTP protocol, often including the HTTPS secure variant and other features and extensions that are considered useful for its planned usage.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] Although web server programs differ in how they are implemented, most of them offer the following common features.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] These are **basic features** that most web servers usually have.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] A few other more **advanced** and popular **features** (*only a very short selection*) are the following ones.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] Once an HTTP request message has been decoded and verified, its values can be used to determine whether that request can be satisfied or not.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] This requires many other steps, including **security checks**.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] The term *URL normalization* refers to the process of modifying and standardizing a URL in a consistent manner.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] There are several types of normalization that may be performed, including the conversion of the scheme and host to lowercase.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] Among the most important normalizations are the removal of "." and ".." path segments and adding trailing slashes to a non-empty path component.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] One or more configuration files of web server may specify the mapping of parts of **URL path** (e.g., initial parts of file path, filename extension and other path components) to a specific URL handler (file, directory, external program or internal module).
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] Web server programs are able to translate an URL path (all or part of it), that refers to a physical file system path, to an absolute path under the target website's root directory.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] Website's root directory may be specified by a configuration file or by some internal rule of the web server by using the name of the website which is the host part of the URL found in HTTP client request.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] The web server appends the path found in requested URL (HTTP request message) and appends it to the path of the (Host) website root directory.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] On an Apache server, this is commonly `/home/www/website` (on Unix machines, usually it is: `/var/www/website`).
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] See the following examples of how it may result.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] The web server then reads the file, if it exists, and sends a response to the client's web browser.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] The response will describe the content of the file and contain the file itself or an error message will return saying that the file does not exist or its access is forbidden.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] The response will describe the content of the directory (list of contained subdirectories and files) or an error message will return saying that the directory does not exist or its access is forbidden.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] For a *dynamic request* the URL path specified by the client should refer to an existing external program (usually an executable file with a CGI) used by the web server to generate dynamic content.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] The web server executes that program, passing in the path-info and the query string `action=view&orderby=thread&date=2021-10-15` so that the program has the info it needs to run.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] (In this case, it will return an HTML document containing a view of forum entries ordered by thread from October 15, 2021).
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] In addition to this, the web server reads data sent from the external program and resends that data to the client that made the request.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] Once a request has been read, interpreted, and verified, it has to be managed depending on its method, its URL, and its parameters, which may include values of HTTP headers.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] That kind of content is called *static* because usually it is not changed by the web server when it is sent to clients and because it remains the same until it is modified (file modification) by some program.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] Response of static file content can be sped up by a **file cache**.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] Most used names for static index files are: `index.html`, `index.htm` and `Default.htm`.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] If a web server program receives a client request message with an URL whose path matches the file name of an existing *file* and that file is accessible by web server program and its attributes match internal rules of web server program, then web server program can send that file to client.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] Usually, for security reasons, most web server programs are pre-configured to serve only regular files or to avoid to use *special file types* like device files, along with symbolic links or hard links to them.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] The aim is to avoid undesirable side effects when serving static web resources.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] If a web server program is capable of **serving dynamic content** and it has been configured to do so, then it is able to communicate with the proper internal module or external program (associated with the requested URL path) in order to pass to it the parameters of the client request.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] After that, the web server program reads from it its data response (that it has generated, often on the fly) and then it resends it to the client program who made the request.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] In order to be able to communicate with its internal modules or external programs, a web server program must have implemented one or more of the many available **gateway interfaces** (see also Web Server Gateway Interfaces used for dynamic content).
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] The three **standard** and historical **gateway interfaces** are the following ones.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] An external CGI program is run by web server program for each dynamic request, then web server program reads from it the generated data response and then resends it to client.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] An external FastCGI program (it usually is a process) is started once by web server program or by some other program or process and then it waits for a network connection which is established permanently by web server; through that connection are sent the request parameters and read data responses.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] A web server program may be capable to manage the dynamic generation (on the fly) of a **directory index list** of files and sub-directories.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] If it cannot be generated an error is returned.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] Usage of dynamically generated *directory listings* is usually avoided or limited to a few selected directories of a website because that generation takes much more OS resources than sending a static index page.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] The main usage of *directory listings* is to allow the download of files (usually when their names, sizes, modification date-times or file attributes may change randomly and frequently) *as they are, without requiring to provide further information to requesting user*.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] In practice whenever there is content that may vary, depending on one or more parameters contained in client request or in configuration settings, then, usually, it is generated dynamically.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] Web server programs are able to send response messages as replies to client request messages.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] An error response message may be sent because a request message could not be successfully read or decoded or analyzed or executed.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] NOTE: the following sections are reported only as examples to help to understand what a web server, more or less, does; these sections are by any means neither exhaustive nor complete.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] When an error response or message is received by a client browser, then if it is related to the main user request (e.g., an URL of a web resource such as a web page) then usually that error message is shown in some browser window or message.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] Example 1: a URL path points to a **directory** name but it does not have a final slash '/' so web server sends a redirect to client in order to instruct it to redo the request with the fixed path name.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] Example 2: a whole set of documents has been **moved inside website** in order to reorganize their file system paths.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] Example 3: a whole set of documents has been **moved to a new website** and now it is mandatory to use secure HTTPS connections to access them.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] Above examples are only a few of the possible kind of redirections.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] A web server program is able to reply to a valid client request message with a successful message, optionally containing requested **web resource data**.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] If web resource data is sent back to client, then it can be **static content** or **dynamic content** depending on how it has been retrieved (from a file or from the output of some program or module).
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] In order to speed up web server responses by lowering average HTTP response times and hardware resources used, many popular web servers implement one or more content caches, each one specialized in a content category.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] In practice, nowadays, many web server programs include their own *userland* **file cache**, tailored for a web server usage and using their specific implementation and parameters.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] The wide spread adoption of RAID and fast solid-state drives (storage hardware with very high I/O speed) has slightly reduced but of course not eliminated the advantage of having a file cache incorporated in a web server.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] Dynamic content, output by an internal module or an external program, may not always change very frequently (given a unique URL with keys or parameters) and so, maybe for a while (e.g., from one second to several hours or more), the resulting output can be cached in RAM or even on a fast disk.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] Anyway, in most cases those kind of caches are implemented by external servers (e.g., reverse proxy) or by storing dynamic data output in separate computers, managed by specific applications (e.g., memcached), in order to not compete for hardware resources (CPU, RAM, disks) with web servers.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] A web server software can be either incorporated into the OS and executed in kernel space, or it can be executed in user space (like other regular applications).
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] Web servers that run in user-mode have to ask the system for permission to use more memory or more CPU resources.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] Not only do these requests to the kernel take time, but they might not always be satisfied because the system reserves resources for its own usage and has the responsibility to share hardware resources with all the other running applications.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] Executing in user mode can also mean using more buffer or data copies (between user-space and kernel-space) which can lead to a decrease in the performance of a user-mode web server.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] Nowadays almost all web server software is executed in user mode (because many of the aforementioned small disadvantages have been overcome by faster hardware, new OS versions, much faster OS system calls and new optimized web server software).
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] See also comparison of web server software to discover which of them run in kernel mode or in user mode (also referred as kernel space or user space).
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] In other words, a **web server should always be very responsive**, even under high load of web traffic, in order to keep **total user's wait** (sum of browser time + network time + **web server response time**) for a response **as low as possible**.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] Among the operating conditions, the **number** (1 ..
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] *n*) of **concurrent client connections** used during a test is an important parameter because it allows to correlate the **concurrency level** supported by web server with results of the tested performance metrics.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] ... used to implement a web server program, **can bias a lot the performances** and in particular the **scalability level** that can be achieved under **heavy load** or when using high end hardware (many CPUs, disks and lots of RAM).
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] In practice some web server software models may require more OS resources (specially more CPUs and more RAM) than others to be able to work well and so to achieve target performances.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p01] Performances of a web server are typically benchmarked by using one or more of the available automated load testing tools.
[src:cherrypy-server/web-server-p02] When a web server is near to or over its load limits, it gets **overloaded** and so it may become **unresponsive**.
